IE 48A - Assignment 3: Esoph and Young People Survey

Irmak Dai

This report consists of two sections. In the first section I will analyze esoph data to see if esophageal cancer is related to age or alcohol & tobacco consumption. Data is from a case-control study of esophageal cancer in Ille-et-Vilaine, France.

In the second section I will work on the dataset Young People Survey’s Hobbies & Interests with the purpose of inferring meaning from the data.

To get more info about this assignment please visit assignment page and IE 48A Course Webpage.

1 Esoph Data Analysis

I noticed that “g/day” exists in some columns

esoph_data$alcgp <- gsub("g/day","",esoph_data$alcgp)
esoph_data$tobgp <- gsub("g/day","",esoph_data$tobgp)

Making them ordered factors again

esoph_data$alcgp <- factor(esoph_data$alcgp, ordered = TRUE, levels = c("0-39","40-79","80-119","120+"))
esoph_data$tobgp <- factor(esoph_data$tobgp, ordered = TRUE, levels = c("0-9","10-19","20-29","30+"))

Creating total patients and ratio of cases column

esoph_data <- esoph_data %>%
  mutate(ntotal=ncases+ncontrols, case_ratio=ncases/ntotal)

Our task is to find relations between variables and whether people have oesophageal cancer or not. The dataset consists of categorical variables instead of linear variables (e.g. we do not have the exact age of the participants). I used the name “case_ratio” instead of “case_probability” since the data is not plentiful, I did not feel comfortable using the term probability.

1.2 Histograms

You can see the histograms in different tabs below:

1.2.1 Number of cases

ggplot(esoph_data, aes(ncases))+
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 1, fill=pal[1])+
  theme_minimal()+
  labs(x="Number of cases",y="Frequency")

There are many groups in which zero or just a few cases exist. There is only one category in which 10+ cases are found.

1.2.2 Number of participants

ggplot(esoph_data, aes(ntotal))+
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 7, fill=pal[2])+
  theme_minimal()+
  labs(x="Number of participants", y="Frequency")

We see that most of the categories have less than 10 participants.

1.2.3 Case ratio

ggplot(esoph_data, aes(case_ratio))+
  geom_histogram(fill=pal[3], binwidth = 0.035)+
  theme_minimal()+
  labs(x="Case ratio among participants", y="Frequency")

Most of the categories have very low case ratios whereas there are considerable number of categories in which ratio is higher than 0.3.

1.3 Relation with age

esoph_by_agegp <- esoph_data %>%
  group_by(agegp) %>%
  summarise(ncases=sum(ncases), ncontrols=sum(ncontrols), ntotal=sum(ntotal))
esoph_by_agegp_arranged <- esoph_by_agegp %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c("ncases","ncontrols"), names_to="case_or_control", values_to="count")

ggplot(esoph_by_agegp_arranged, aes(x=agegp,y=count,fill=case_or_control, label=paste(round(count/ntotal,3)*100,"%")))+
  geom_bar(stat = "identity")+
  scale_fill_manual(values=pal)+
  theme_minimal()+
  geom_text(position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5))+
  labs(x = "Age Group", y = "Count", title = "Number of participants among age groups")

We see that number of participants varies in age groups.
The fact that case ratio of 65-74 age group is higher than 75+ age group may be interesting. This may be caused by the fact that 75+ age group has relatively less participants, or maybe people who develop esophageal cancer may not live that longer. Nevertheless we have enough evidence to say that esophageal cancer is more common in the older age groups, thus is related to age.

ggplot(esoph_by_agegp, aes(x="",y=ncases/sum(ncases),fill=agegp, label=ncases/sum(ncases)))+
  geom_bar(stat="identity",width=1)+coord_polar("y")+
  labs(x="",y="Breakdown of esophageal cancer patients according to age groups")+
  scale_fill_discrete(name="Age groups")+
  geom_text(position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5), angle=60)+
  scale_fill_manual(values = pal)

We see that most of the esophageal cancer patients that participated in this research belong the age groups “55-64”, “65-74” and “45-54”. This pie chart would br very different if number of participants in the different age groups were equal.

esoph_by_alcgp <- esoph_data %>%

It is clear that people who consume alcohol more are more likely to develop esopheagal cancer. It is worth to remark the significant difference between case ratios of “0-39” and “40-79” alcohol consumption groups.

ggplot(esoph_by_alcgp, aes(x="",y=ncases/sum(ncases),fill=alcgp, label=ncases/sum(ncases)))+
  geom_bar(stat="identity",width=1)+coord_polar("y")+

  scale_fill_discrete(name="Alcohol consumption (g/day)")+

  scale_fill_manual(values = pal)

Even if “80-119” and “120+” alcohol consumption groups constitute a small part of the participants, we see that they constitute a large part of cancer patients.

esoph_by_alcgp_tobgp <- esoph_data %>%

1.6 Logistic Regression

Here is a logistic regression model to predict proportion of cases among participants.

* Science and technology, mathematics and physics
* Medicine, biology and chemistry
* Writing, art exhibitions and theatre
Whereas it may be interesting how “Law” and “Fun with friends” are closely located.

2.4 K-Means

set.seed(15)
subject_cluster <- kmeans(mds_data, centers=5)
mds_clusters <- data.frame(subject=names(subject_cluster$cluster),cluster_mds=subject_cluster$cluster) %>% arrange(cluster_mds,subject)

ggplot(data.frame(mds_data) %>% 
         mutate(clusters=as.factor(subject_cluster$cluster),subjects=rownames(mds_data)),aes(x=x,y=y)) + 
  geom_text(aes(label=subjects,color=clusters),angle=45,size=2) + 
  geom_point(data=as.data.frame(subject_cluster$centers),aes(x=x,y=y)) +
  theme_minimal()

2.5 Hierarchial Clustering

I tried the methods “single”, “complete”, “average”, “centroid” and “ward.D2”. But I chose these ones to report, since they are more easy to read and I think that they respresent the relations better.

Similarly we see related subjects in the same clusters such as
* Medicine, biology and chemistry
* Internet and PC
* Celebrities and shopping

2.5.1 Complete

hc_complete <- hclust(as.dist(dist_matrix), method = "complete")
plot(hc_complete, hang = -1)

2.5.2 Average

hc_average <- hclust(as.dist(dist_matrix), method = "average")
plot(hc_average, hang = -1)

2.5.3 Ward.D2

hc_ward <- hclust(as.dist(dist_matrix), method = "ward.D2")
plot(hc_ward, hang = -1)
